   =20
    <h4 id=3D"previmg" class=3D"largeTopMargin">Example 3: Using the Previo=
us Image</h4>=20
    <p>
      In ray tracing, it is often required to continuously improve a render=
ing result over time. To this end, the emulator allows
      rendering multiple consecutive image frames and the shader of the cur=
rent frame gets access to the previously rendered frame.
    </p>
    <p>
      The total number of rendered image frames can be changed in the <b>Ed=
it Scene</b> section of the user interface.
     =20
    </p><p>In the shader, the total number of frames is known via the unifo=
rm integer variable <code>frameSize</code>. The current frame number (start=
ing=20
      from 0) is given by the uniform integer variable <code>frameID</code>=
.
    </p>
    <p>
      In this example, the first image (with <code>frameID</code> =3D 0) is=
 set to black. Each new frame reads the pixel value
      from the previous output image and adds a small color offset, such th=
at over time, the image fades to white.
    </p>
       <pre class=3D"myHackyShaderHighlight" style=3D"color:#000000;backgro=
und:#eee; margin-top:0px; font-size: 0.8em;"><span style=3D"color:#930f80;"=
>void</span> main() { <span style=3D"color:darkgreen;">/**** RAY GENERATION=
 SHADER ****/</span>
  <span style=3D"color:#930f80;">if</span>(frameID =3D=3D<span style=3D"col=
or:blue;"> 0</span>) {
     <span style=3D"color:darkgreen;">// initialize with black
</span>     gsnSetPixel(<span style=3D"color:#930f80;">vec4</span>(<span st=
