    <h4 id=3D"reflections" class=3D"largeTopMargin">Example 10: Reflections=
 / Avoiding Recursion</h4>
    <p>For ray hits on a reflective surface, the reflected ray can be calcu=
lated and traced into the scene.
      In a first simple model, we assume that the radiance at a surface poi=
nt is the sum of the=20
      direct light from the light source plus the radiance contribution fro=
m the reflected ray.
       The reflected ray might be reflected again at the next hit.
       The ray tracer only stops at non-reflective surfaces.=20
       Therefore, the number of reflections must be limited, otherwise, the=
re might be an endless loop.  =20
    </p>
     <div class=3D"centeredImage">
      <img class=3D"image" src=3D"https://www.gsn-lib.org/docs/nodes/images=
/raytrace/reflections.png" width=3D"512" alt=3D"reflections">
    </div>=20
    <p>
           Reflections can be implemented very easily with recursive functi=
on calls:
    </p>
 <pre class=3D"myHackyShaderHighlight" style=3D"color:#000000;background:#e=
ee; margin-top:0px; font-size: 0.8em;">trace(level, ray, &amp;color) { <spa=
n style=3D"color:darkgreen;">// THIS IS PSEUDOCODE!!!
</span>  <span style=3D"color:#930f80;">if</span> (intersect(ray, &amp;hit)=
) {=20
    shadow =3D testShadow(hit);
    directColor =3D getDirectLight(hit, shadow);
    <span style=3D"color:#930f80;">if</span> (reflectionFactor &gt; <span s=
tyle=3D"color:blue;">0.0</span> &amp;&amp; level &lt; maxLevel) {
      reflectedRay =3D <span style=3D"color:#ff8c00;">reflect</span>(ray, h=
it.normal);
      trace(level +<span style=3D"color:blue;"> 1</span>, reflectedRay, &am=
p;reflectionColor); <span style=3D"color:darkgreen;">// recursion
</span>    }
    color =3D color + directColor + reflectionFactor * reflectionColor;
  } <span style=3D"color:#930f80;">else</span> {
    color =3D backgroundColor;
  }
}
</pre>
    <p>However, when working with ray tracing shaders, the
         number of recursive function calls should be kept as low as possib=
le.=20
         Fortunately, the same result can also be achieved without recursio=
n:</p>
<pre class=3D"myHackyShaderHighlight" style=3D"color:#000000;background:#ee=
e; margin-top:0px; font-size: 0.8em;">trace(ray, &amp;color) { <span style=
=3D"color:darkgreen;">// THIS IS PSEUDOCODE!!!
</span>  nextRay =3D ray; =20
  contribution =3D <span style=3D"color:blue;">1.0</span>;
  level =3D<span style=3D"color:blue;"> 0</span>;
  while (nextRay &amp;&amp; level &lt; maxLevel) {
    <span style=3D"color:#930f80;">if</span> (intersect(nextRay, &amp;hit))=
 {
      shadow =3D testShadow(hit);
      directColor =3D getDirectLight(hit, shadow);
      <span style=3D"color:#930f80;">if</span> (reflectionFactor &gt; <span=
 style=3D"color:blue;">0.0</span>) {
        reflectedRay =3D <span style=3D"color:#ff8c00;">reflect</span>(next=
Ray, hit.normal);
        nextRay =3D reflectedRay;
      } <span style=3D"color:#930f80;">else</span> {
        nextRay =3D false;
      }
    } <span style=3D"color:#930f80;">else</span> {
      directColor =3D backgroundColor;
      nextRay =3D false;
    }
    color =3D color + contribution * directColor;
    contribution =3D contribution * reflectionFactor;
    level =3D level +<span style=3D"color:blue;"> 1</span>;
  }
}
</pre>
