     <a href=3D"https://www.gsn-lib.org/apps/raytracing/index.php?name=3Dex=
ample_antialiasing" class=3D"externalLink">
      <img class=3D"image" src=3D"https://www.gsn-lib.org/docs/nodes/images=
/raytrace/example_antialiasing.png" width=3D"600" alt=3D"example_antialiasi=
ng"><br data-filtered=3D"filtered">
     open example</a>
    </div>
   =20
    <h4 id=3D"distraytracing" class=3D"largeTopMargin">Example 12: Distribu=
ted Ray Tracing / Soft Shadows</h4>
    <p><a href=3D"https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/964965.808590" class=3D"ex=
ternalLink">Distributed Ray Tracing</a> (Cook et al., Siggraph 1984)=20
       is not only suitable for anti-aliasing but it can also be used to cr=
eate soft shadows.
       To this end, the position on an area light source is varied randomly=
 (with a uniform distribution).
       Further applications of distributed ray tracing are glossy surfaces,=
 motion blur, depth of field, etc.
    </p>
    <div class=3D"centeredImage">
      <img class=3D"image" src=3D"https://www.gsn-lib.org/docs/nodes/images=
/raytrace/softshadow.png" width=3D"600" alt=3D"softshadow">
    </div>   =20
     <div class=3D"centeredImage">
     <a href=3D"https://www.gsn-lib.org/apps/raytracing/index.php?name=3Dex=
ample_softshadows" class=3D"externalLink">
      <img class=3D"image" src=3D"https://www.gsn-lib.org/docs/nodes/images=
/raytrace/example_softshadows.jpg" width=3D"600" alt=3D"example_softshadows=
"><br data-filtered=3D"filtered">
     open example</a>
    </div>   =20
    <h4 id=3D"pathtracing" class=3D"largeTopMargin">Example 13: Path Tracin=
g</h4>
    <p>If distributed ray tracing was used for indirect light (e.g.&nbsp;fo=
r indirect diffuse reflection)=20
      this would quickly result in problems as the number of rays grows exp=
onentially.
      The indirections of a higher degree
     have a smaller contribution to the image but use significantly more ra=
ys than the lower indirections.
    </p>
    <div class=3D"centeredImage">
      <img class=3D"image" src=3D"https://www.gsn-lib.org/docs/nodes/images=
/raytrace/path_tracing.png" width=3D"300" alt=3D"path_tracing">
    </div>  =20
    <p><a href=3D"https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/15886.15902" class=3D"exte=
rnalLink">Path Tracing</a> (Kajiya, Siggraph 1986) provides
      a solution to this problem by selecting only 1 ray from all possible =
rays at each hit.=20
      This creates 1 path per primary ray. The idea is to trace many=20
      different paths per camera pixel and calculate the mean. The advantag=
e of this approach is that all
      indirections receive the same computational effort.
    </p>
    <p>
      The path tracing example in this section uses a simple model with two=
 different materials:
      An ideal refraction for the sphere on the left and
      a diffuse reflection everywhere else. The diffuse reflection
      is computed by the sum of the direct component (from the light source=
)
      and the indirect diffuse reflection (from all directions). The result=
ing=20
      rendering in the=20
      <a href=3D"https://www.graphics.cornell.edu/online/box/history.html" =
class=3D"externalLink">Cornell&nbsp;Box</a>=20
      contains the famous "color bleeding" from the colored wall
      onto the nearby surfaces.
    </p>
     <div class=3D"centeredImage">
     <a href=3D"https://www.gsn-lib.org/apps/raytracing/index.php?name=3Dex=
ample_pathtracing" class=3D"externalLink">
      <img class=3D"image" src=3D"https://www.gsn-lib.org/docs/nodes/images=
/raytrace/example_pathtracing.jpg" width=3D"320" alt=3D"example_pathtracing=
"><br data-filtered=3D"filtered">
     open example</a>
    </div>   =20

    <h4 id=3D"pathtracing" class=3D"largeTopMargin">Example 14: Path Tracin=
